# NestJS Backend Rules

## Architecture
- Module per domain: `auth`, `users`, `catalogue`, `videos`, `analytics`, `generation`.
- Controller → Service → Repository. Controllers are thin: validation + delegation only.
- DTOs with `class-validator` on every endpoint; global `ValidationPipe({whitelist: true})`.
- Config via `@nestjs/config`; secrets only from `.env` (never committed). Required keys fail fast at boot.

## Database (Supabase Postgres)
- Access Postgres directly (TypeORM or Prisma — pick one, stay consistent) using the Supabase connection string. Supabase Auth may be used for JWT issuance; verify JWTs in a NestJS guard.
- Migrations in `backend/migrations/`, one per feature, reversible.
- Core tables: users, profiles, catalogue_topics, catalogue_interests, videos, video_scenes, watch_events, quiz_unlocks (future).
- Analytics reads are SQL aggregates (peak hour = `date_trunc('hour')` group-by on watch_events); no in-memory aggregation of full tables.

## Video generation pipeline
- `generation` module owns: scene templating (optional Exa research), ElevenLabs TTS, **progressive EVENT HLS packaging** (ffmpeg), timeline assembly.
- Live delivery: `POST /videos` → 202 with `hlsUrl`; packager appends `.ts` segments as each scene finishes; finalize writes `#EXT-X-ENDLIST`.
- ElevenLabs: model `eleven_flash_v2_5`. EVERY call goes through `TtsService.getOrSynthesize`. Fixtures when `NODE_ENV=test|dev-offline`.
- Remotion rendering is OPTIONAL export path only. Media on disk (`HLS_ROOT`), served via `/media/:videoId/:file` — Render disk or local; no S3.

## API conventions
- REST, plural nouns, versioned prefix `/api/v1`. Errors: standard shape `{statusCode, message, error}` via exception filters.
- Auth guard on everything except /auth/*. User id always from JWT, never from request body.

## Quality gates
- Each service has at least one happy-path unit test (Jest). e2e via supertest for auth + videos.
- No `console.log`; use Nest Logger.
